{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"MONSTERS\n        The Calculator\n      \n\n      \n        \n        \n          Film · Director\n          ROMANPOLANSKI\n        \n\n        \n        \n          The art is undeniably masterful. The man is undeniably a monster. Every stream is a vote.\n        \n\n        \n        \n          \n            8.0\n            The Monster\n          \n          \n            8.7\n            The Art\n          \n        \n\n        \n        \n          \n            Consumability Index\n          \n          34\n        \n      \n    \n    \n      A. Tabloid Front Page\n      Red banner, screaming headline, but with editorial typography and pull quotes. Like a highbrow magazine that's lost its mind. The red bar is the tabloid; the serif italic is the essay underneath.","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1773438408676}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"MONSTERS\n          Should you?\n        \n      \n\n      \n        \n        VERDICT\n\n        \n        Roman Polanski\n        Filmmaker · Chinatown, The Pianist, Rosemary's Baby\n\n        \n        \n          \n            The Monster\n            8.0\n            Convicted. Fled. Repeat allegations.\n          \n          \n            The Art\n            8.7\n            Genre-defining. Oscar-winning. Singular.\n          \n        \n\n        \n        \n          \n            Consumability\n            You do the math.\n          \n          34\n        \n      \n    \n    \n      B. Magazine Spread with Tabloid Edge\n      Clean magazine layout with a newspaper masthead, but the red \"VERDICT\" tag and blunt one-liners give it tabloid bite. More New Yorker-meets-Daily-Mail. The restraint makes the content hit harder.","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1773438410013}
